Deuteronomy (variant file)

-Bible:OldGreek:Pentateuch:Deuteronomy (005)

-Prepared for free non-commercial use by the Center for Computer Assisted Tools for Septuagint Studies (CATSS)
  at the University of Pennsylvania, Center for Computer Analysis of Texts (CCAT)
-Filesize uncompressed: about 2.8 M
-Center for Computer Analysis of Texts (Robert A. Kraft)
 Claudia Cohen Hall (formerly Logan Hall), University of Pennsylvania,
 Philadelphia PA 19104-6304 USA; kraft[at]ccat.sas.upenn.edu

This material was initially encoded ca, 1997 by Gil Renberg, based on and in cooperation with the Septuaginta: Vetus Testamentum Graecum auctoritate Societatis Litterarum Gottingensis editum, vol. 3.2, Deuteronomium, ed. John W. Wevers (Goettingen: Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht, 1977), supplemented with more recent information or discoveries where available. An English version of the Introduction also has been prepared for CATSS by John W. Wevers and edited for online use by R. A. Kraft (2006).

unicode hypertext edition: November, 2005, by Christopher McCartney

-File format is described by Robert Kraft, "Treatment of the Greek Textual Variants"
in Computer Assisted Tools for Septuagint Studies (CATSS), vol. 1: Ruth, Septuagint and Cognate Studies 20 (Scholars Press, 1986).
-Categories of variants are marked thus --
">" = lacking in the following witnesses,
"+" = longer text,
":" = alternative reading,
transpositions are treated as plus/minus readings, with "~" added to indicate transposition
[original coding also included the following]
@@@ indicates indentation in the published text [no need to retain]
<it>...</> indicates italics [which can now be indicated in html],
and <lt>...</> indicates Latin words and phrases [now changed to italics];
for the Greek transliterations, TLG "Beta Code" had been used [now changed to unicode].
-Text divisions are marked by "~" at left margin, followed by "a" to designate the book, "x" for chapter, and "y" for verse; explicit numbers have been added for the user's convenience -- thus "~x2y5" = chapter 2, verse 5 [which now needs to be simplified].

This is the penultimate draft of the text and variants file for Greek LXX Deuteronomy, edited most recently (10/1997) by Gil Renberg in four files (1-7, 8-16, 17-27, 28-e) which are combined here for more convenient searching. Many editorial queries and calls for verification or correction appeared in the beta file (in bold type) [update: the bold font did not survive the transition to unicode (see the "beta" version) -- Chris McCartney], but rather than hold this material back from circulation until there is time to edit it more fully, we hereby make it available with this warning about its unfinished character. Renberg's queries and notes to each file have been moved to the beginning for convenience.

[[Renberg notes and Kraft comments:
Things to look for:
Anything in boldface [no longer present].
I have used <sy> in several cases when the manuscript was Syh, even though the ap.crit. shows Latin letters rather than Syriac. [ok; the Syh version is cited (no Sy as such), so this is unambiguous and Syriac would need to be supplied]
I used <lt>Dt</> instead of <it>Dt</>. [program to italic]
There are many abbreviations that need to be put in a proper format.
Look for (|) and (||), whatever they are. Most of them are in boldface.
Sublinear dots are shown by {?}. Supralinear items are enclosed in {..}.
I’m not sure what to do when there is a variant given within a bracket, like this:
ωορδ 53’ (ωορδϝαριαντ 53) 767 B F]]

[Renberg on file 2]
Bear in mind:
Used <lt>Dt</> instead of <it>Dt</>.
Am using κ_σ_ for KURIOS abbreviation, θ_σ_ for QEOS, ets.
For superscript within superscript am using {<s..>s}. E.g., <it>f</>{-56<stxt>s}. I’ve put each in boldface to make finding them easier.
Note that there is a difference between (sub % Syh) and (sub # Syh). (E.g., see verses 9:26-7.)
Verses 12:6-18.22 require massive omission for witness 767. I held off, hoping that this can be done automatically.
See note at very end about omissions in Chapt. 17.
I have opted to describe homoteleuta of only three words with (>3 homoi.), since it would be a pain to find these if you change your mind about witness blocks of less than four, and since if you don’t want them, it would be easy enough to find them and remove the (>3 homoi.)…(>3).
Similarly, I have used (+3 dittogr.)…(+3), and these also can be found easily enough and changed if need be.
Am using <s>…</> for Greek variants with the final letter in superscript. (All such instances can easily be found by doing a search for “</></>”, since this is the only time </></> is used.
Check on my use of “..” when combining and dividing variants. (Do search for “..”.)

Verses 17:2-15 get the following omission:
(>561) 527 (>561)
